"local means have failed. As discussed earlier, humanitarian action by defi nition amounts to substitution. That being said, the extent of this substitution must be determined, as must the role and responsibilities of humanitarian actors with respect to local services and organizations. The competencies of the latter should provide the answer: the more competent they are, the more useful it is to rely on them. The less competent they are, the more capacity-building is justifi ed, and this is not always compatible with humanitarian action and is certainly not its primary role. The overarching priority, after all, is the impact of humanitarian operations on the circumstances of the victims, who should not have to pay the price for incompetence, corruption, and the failings of local means. As mentioned earlier, the ethical attitude consists in recognizing their role and, if possible, involving them directly. Implementation is then determined by local reality and may range from complete substitution to complete support,"